text:
Nurture your soul, that treasure of divine might,  
Crafted to sip from the chalice of the heavens,  
Free from guilt’s heavy chains, disdainful of vice,  
Ready, by the grace of gods, to dance toward virtue.  
Guard it fiercely, lest your reckless journey  
Plunge it into the abyss of eternal agony.  

Tend to your body, yes, but let your soul lead;  
Slice away the excess, let sustenance be pure;  
Conquer pride with garments that don’t enslave,  
Seek wisdom’s treasure, shun ignorance's cruel grip.  
Feed and clothe the flesh, but do not let them devour  
The essence of both soul and body in their hunger.  

Care for this world, let your body thrive;  
Do not twist your mind in pursuit of shadowy gains;  
Do not crush the weak with unjust might;  
Pay your dues without delay, let justice reign.  
Spend wisely, with an eye on those in need,  
And remember, in all, the heart of compassion.  

Cherish your soul, your steadfast anchor;  
Honor your body for your soul’s delight;  
Tend to this world, a cradle for your flesh;  
But care, oh care, so that virtue shines bright.  
Care in such a way that you can be assured:  
Let not your cares bar you from heaven’s bliss.

